e reforms tended to assume as their ideal borrower someone who was white, propertied, and male. In subsequent decades, the emancipatory promise of debtors’ rights would be tested as women, wage earners, and African Americans seized on their language to challenge other structural inequalities: the dependency of marriage, the exploitation of industrial capitalism, and the oppression of Jim Crow. By reconstructing these forgotten developments—and recovering the experiences of indebted farmwives, sharecroppers, and wage workers—The Price of Misfortune narrates a new history of inequality, coercion, and law amid the early financialization of American capitalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aConsumersxCivil rightszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aDebtxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 0aDebtor and creditorzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aDebtor and creditorzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aFinance, PersonalxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  alegal history, finance capitalism, debtors' rights, inequality, coercion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079732940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226734033423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226734033/original  a978-3-11-079732-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131913-